There werethreeeminent men of the name Caius Scribonius Curio, auus, pater, filius, Ptin h. n. v11 41, uua fareeilia Curionum in qua tres continua serie oratores extiterunt. The first (Curio pater) was a distinguished orator (elaqum tissimus temporibus suis de orat. 11 δ 98, Brut. ἓ rar), who spoke 'nst Servius Fulvius, when accused of incest. The second is the one re erred to in the text and again 11 ἓ 59. He was tribune of the plebs nc. 90, and, after serving under Sulla in Greece‚ became praetor nc. 82 and consul ne. 76. At the expiration of his consulship he was made pro consul of Macedonia, where he carried the war against the barbarinos as far north as the Danube, and celebrated a triumph over the Dardanians in 71 (in Pis. ἕ 44). An intimate friend and supporter of Cicero, he entertained a personal enmity to Caesar, which was probably the cause why he spoke in favour of Clodius when accused of violating the sacra of the Bona Dea: in nc. 57 he was made pontifex maximus Cicero speaks highly of him as a man, (ep. ad Quint. fr. 11 3, a, in Vatin. ἕ ²4 perpetuum bostem improborum omnium, auctorem publici consilii, libertale communi tuenda maxime liberum), but he did not shine as an orator, mator Lutine uon pessime loqcubatur, sea’ erat indoctus, memoria nulla, actebue ridiculus, Brut. 5213, 5 arb-arnis aaa. His son was also a friend of Cicero, the first seven letters of whose second book of epistulae ad sanctiores are addressed to him, but unlike his father, a profligate. He was married to Fulvia, who afterwards became Antony’s wife. He was one of the main instrumeuts in kindling the war between Caesar and Pompcy and on the breaking out of the war served under Caesar and fell in battle against Juba and the Pompeian party.
